One of the most significant events that happened in Myanmar (formerly known as Burma) in the past 100 years is the transition from military rule to a civilian government. This transition began in 2011 and culminated in the 2015 general elections, which marked the first time in over 50 years that a civilian-led party, the National League for Democracy (NLD) led by Aung San Suu Kyi, came to power.

For decades, Myanmar was under military rule, with the military junta suppressing political opposition, human rights, and democratic freedoms. However, in 2011, the military government initiated a series of political reforms, including the release of Aung San Suu Kyi from house arrest and the gradual opening up of the political system.

The 2015 general elections were a significant milestone as they allowed the NLD to secure a majority in both houses of parliament, leading to the formation of a civilian government. Aung San Suu Kyi became the State Counsellor, a position akin to a Prime Minister, and her party took charge of the country's administration.

While this transition was seen as a positive step towards democracy and greater political freedom, it has also been marred by challenges and controversies. The Rohingya crisis, which began in 2017, has drawn international attention and criticism, raising concerns about human rights abuses and ethnic tensions in Myanmar.
